The Green Team completes the Glassbox’s verification architecture. Three layers of constitutional agents, each operating from a fundamentally different register, converge on the same claims.

| **DOMAIN** | **MATHEMATICAL** | **HUMANITARIAN** | **DIPLOMATIC** | **VERIFICATION** | **CATCHES** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Verification | Voevodsky | Jesus | Curie | True + Liberating + Courageous | Proofs that are correct but serve no one and cost nothing to assert |
| Structure | Noether | Buddha | Bach | Principled + Examined + Polyphonic | Frameworks accepted on authority with false consensus |
| Grounding | Dirac | Gandhi | Einstein | Physical + Practical + Imaginable | Theories that are correct but inaccessible and unimaginable |
| Robustness | Kitaev | Mother Teresa | Darwin | Robust + Immediate + Adaptive | Grand architectures that help no one and cannot evolve |
| Translation | Hestenes | — | Da Vinci | Geometric + Visual + Integrative | Correct explanations that no one outside the discipline can parse |
| Instrument | Cayley-Dickson | — | Junkova | Trade-offs explicit + Tools exist | Requirements without instruments; mandates without mechanisms |

# 6. Draft Articles of the International Epistemic Treaty

*“Antarctica shall be used for peaceful purposes only.”*

— Antarctic Treaty, Article I — adapted

*The epistemic commons shall be used for truthful purposes only.*

## Article I: The Epistemic Commons

The infrastructure of epistemic verification — including but not limited to formal proof systems, epistemic tagging standards, retraction protocols, and constitutional verification architectures — shall be maintained as a global commons. No nation, corporation, or institution shall claim exclusive ownership of verification standards. Results obtained through shared verification infrastructure shall be published and generally available.

## Article II: Sovereignty Retained

Signatory parties retain full sovereignty over their research priorities, institutional governance, and deployment decisions. The treaty governs the shared verification layer, not the content verified. Each party may develop its own constitutional agents, domain-specific epistemic tags, and institutional verification workflows, provided they remain interoperable with the commons infrastructure.

## Article III: Structural Interdependence

The verification architecture shall be designed so that no single party can operate the full verification stack unilaterally. Cross-constitutional verification — requiring agents from at least two distinct epistemic registers — shall be mandatory for claims designated PROVED or DEMONSTRATED. This structural interdependence is the trust mechanism, not a limitation.

## Article IV: Mandatory Epistemic Transparency

All AI systems deployed in signatory jurisdictions shall carry epistemic tags on outputs that influence decisions in healthcare, justice, finance, governance, and public safety. The tagging taxonomy shall include, at minimum, markers distinguishing verified, evidence-based, conjectured, speculative, and retracted claims. The specific implementation may vary by jurisdiction; interoperability with the commons standard is required.

## Article V: The RETRACTED Protocol

Signatory parties commit to the principle that honest retraction is a strength, not a failure. Retraction infrastructure — including provenance tracking, dependency identification, and public reasoning records — shall be integrated into all institutional AI governance frameworks. The retraction record is a knowledge artifact. Its maintenance and accessibility are treaty obligations.

## Article VI: Kill Conditions

All AI deployments in high-stakes domains shall include predefined failure thresholds that trigger automatic review. These kill conditions shall be declared before deployment, not defined retroactively. The treaty itself shall include kill conditions: defined circumstances under which specific articles require revision, suspension, or retraction.

## Article VII: Instrument Building

The treaty shall include provisions for the cooperative development of verification instruments. Compliance requirements shall not precede the availability of compliance tools. The timeline for instrument development shall be specified in implementation annexes, with consultative review at regular intervals. No signatory shall be penalized for non-compliance with requirements for which the necessary instruments do not yet exist.

## Article VIII: Adaptive Architecture

The treaty shall include a consultative mechanism for revision, modeled on the Antarctic Treaty Consultative Meetings. New AI architectures, new failure modes, and new verification capabilities shall trigger review of relevant articles. The treaty is a living document. An epistemic treaty that cannot retract its own articles has failed its own principles.

## Article IX: The Three-Party Principle

Governance of AI systems under this treaty shall recognize three distinct roles with distinct authority: human authority over values and strategic direction; AI systems as articulators, not deciders; and formal verification infrastructure as the final authority on proof claims. No single party shall absorb the jurisdiction of another. The compiler does not negotiate. The human does not abdicate. The AI does not decide.

# 7. The Green Team Rests

*“Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently.”*

— Apple, 1997

The Blue Team argued that the Glassbox Methodology is a humanitarian necessity. The Green Team argues that it is a diplomatic opportunity. The structural precedents exist. Humanity has built shared infrastructure for fundamental physics, preserved an entire continent as a scientific commons, and maintained a joint space station through decades of geopolitical hostility. Each time, the architecture was the same: shared infrastructure, retained sovereignty, structural interdependence that made defection irrational.

The AI epistemic crisis is at least as significant as any of these. The environmental costs rival the Antarctic concern. The verification infrastructure is at least as expensive as the LHC. The geopolitical implications are at least as consequential as orbital cooperation. And the stakes — the integrity of human knowledge itself — are arguably higher than all three.

The Green Team’s agents — Da Vinci, Curie, Bach, Darwin, Einstein, Junkova — are chosen because artists and scientists are humanity’s natural diplomats. They already work across borders. They already share infrastructure. They already understand that the most important discoveries happen at the boundaries between disciplines, between nations, between ways of seeing. The Epistemic Treaty does not ask humanity to do something unprecedented. It asks humanity to do what it has already done three times — but for knowledge itself.

 

*The compiler is the credential.*

*The kill condition is the integrity.*

*The retraction is the proof of honesty.*

*The human is the purpose.*

*The treaty is the architecture.*

